-- China shares rise, policy moves boost auto, property stocks
-- By Grace Li
-- Fri Jul 11, 2014 03:07AM EDT
-- None



HONG KONG, July 11 (Reuters) - China shares edged up on Friday, lifted by solid gains for carmakers and property developers, which investors expect to benefit from policy changes.

The Shanghai Composite Index <.SSEC> rose 0.4 percent at 2,046.96 points. The CSI300 <.CSI300> of the leading Shanghai and Shenzhen A-share listings inched up 0.2 percent. On the week, the two indexes were down 0.6 and 1.4 percent, respectively, their first weekly loss in three. China Vanke <000002.SZ>, the country's largest residential property developer, gained 1.4 percent, the top CSI300 boost. Poly Real Estate <600048.SS> rose 2.6 percent.  On Thursday, Jinan in eastern Shandong province removed restrictions on home purchases, sparking hopes more cities will follow suit. [ID:nL4N0PL2DF]